==English==
===Etymology===
From Old French ''[[arismetique]]'', from {{L.}} ''[[arithmetica]]'', from Greek [[αριθμητικη]] ([[τεχνη]]), counting (art), from [[αριθμος]], number
{{etystub}}<!--The Greek etymons require accents and stated to be either Ancient (more likely) or Modern Greek-->
[[Category:Greek derivations]]

===Pronunciation===
*(''noun''): ərĭth'mətĭk, /əˈrɪθmətɪk/, /<tt>@"rITm@tIk</tt>/
*(''adjective: of or relating to arithmetic''): ''as for the noun''
*(''adjective: computed using addition rather than multiplication''): ărĭthmĕ'tĭk, /ærɪθˈmɛtɪk/, /<tt>{rIT"mEtIk</tt>/
[[Category:English heteronyms]]

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
'''arithmetic''' (''[[uncountable]]'')

#{{mathematics}} The [[mathematics]] of [[number]]s ([[integer]]s, [[rational number]]s, [[real number]]s, or [[complex number]]s) under the [[operation]]s of [[addition]], [[subtraction]], [[multiplication]], [[division]], raising to [[power]]s and [[extraction]] of [[root]]s..

====Derived terms====
<!--terms derived from the noun-->
*[[location arithmetic]]
*[[saturation arithmetic]]

